How to check the APIs in both the source codes

Great — this is exactly the right technical question.
When you say “check APIs,” what you really want is:

👉 **“What functions, structures, macros, and interfaces changed between 5.15 and 6.1?”**

Here’s how you do it properly (this is how kernel engineers do it 👇)

---

# 🔹 1. Compare Function APIs (Core Method)

## ✅ Use `git diff` (BEST way)

```bash
git diff v5.15..v6.1 -- net/bluetooth include/net/bluetooth
```

👉 This shows:

* Added/removed functions
* Function signature changes
* Struct changes

---

## 🔍 Example (What to Look For)

You may see changes like:

```c
int hci_connect(struct hci_dev *hdev, ...)
```

→ becomes

```c
int hci_connect(struct hci_dev *hdev, struct bt_iso_qos *qos, ...)
```

👉 This means:

* API changed ❗
* Your 5.15 code won’t match → must adapt

---

# 🔹 2. Track Individual Function Changes

If you already know a function (like `hci_conn_add`):

```bash
git log -p v5.15..v6.1 -- net/bluetooth/hci_conn.c
```

👉 Shows:

* Who changed it
* What exactly changed
* Why (commit message = gold 💡)

---

# 🔹 3. Compare Header Files (VERY IMPORTANT)

Most APIs are defined in headers:

```bash
diff -u \
include/net/bluetooth/hci_core.h \
/path/to/6.1/include/net/bluetooth/hci_core.h
```

👉 Look for:

* New structs (`bt_iso_qos`, etc.)
* Enum changes
* Macro additions

---

## 🔴 Why Headers Matter

Even if `.c` files compile:

👉 Missing struct fields = runtime crash ❌

---

# 🔹 4. Use `cscope` / `ctags` (Faster Navigation)

Generate tags:

```bash
ctags -R net/bluetooth include/net/bluetooth
```

Then:

* Jump to function definitions
* Compare quickly across versions

---

# 🔹 5. Check for New Files (Like iso.c)

```bash
git diff --name-status v5.15..v6.1 | grep bluetooth
```

👉 Shows:

* New files (e.g., `iso.c`)
* Modified files
* Deleted files

---

# 🔹 6. Focus Areas for LE Audio APIs

Don’t try to check everything — focus here:

### ✔ ISO Layer

* `iso.c`, `iso.h`
* socket APIs

---

### ✔ HCI Layer

